
[1]rampant

   RAMP'ANT, a. [See Ramp and Ramble.]

   1. Overgrowing the usual bounds; rank in growth; exuberant; as rampant
   weeds.

   2. Overleaping restraint; as rampant vice.

   3. In heraldry, applied to the lion, leopard or other beast, rampant
   denotes the animal reared and standing on his hind legs, in the posture
   of climbing. It differs from saliant, which indicates the posture of
   springing or making a sally.

   The lion rampant shakes his brinded mane.
